posts.name: Carlton D'Silva
posts.cooked:
Hi Rishab,

From my meeting with operations: I was clearly told that if students do not use quotes there will be errors for some students. In other words, if you want to make sure your answers are correctly parsed by the grader (which is not the same as the front end validator which gives you the error), you MUST use double quotes for strings. This is the technical explanation - its a CSV. If your string has commas, then the answer key parser will consider the answer as wrong. Obviously this does not affect everyone. String answers that do not have a comma are not affected. But string answers that have a comma WILL get affected. Thats the explanation. The frontend validator is not the grader. They are two separate things. The back end grader was tested, the front end is a new UI and thus has new scripts some of which are obviously buggy, but it does not decide your score.

I understand your frustrations perfectly well. I can only report what I have been told. I do not run the backend. I have informed them and brought up all these issues to their attention. They are well aware of the issues. You will have an opportunity to give feedback in TDS and this feedback will be anonymous. We will release this feedback form at the end of the term.

Kind regards

posts.name: Carlton D'Silva

Just to reiterate what Sarath and Anupam has said,

go through this discourse thread carefully and you will find the solution to your issues.

Initially, there was a bug in the front end UI when quotes were used. But this was fixed when it was brought to our attention. But this never affects your actual grading. Because the grader is different from the front end UI.
From our side:
We took a sample of some submissions where students have claimed that, all their answers were correct, and the problem was with the quotes.
Our findings:
None of those submissions had all correct answers. The string quotes were not the problem. They actually had wrong answers in their submission (usually numericals).

Together with JK, I have also looked at how the parsing works and we are confident that currently it works as expected. Nevertheless we still took some samples from students that claimed to have issues to make sure there were no problems. In every case we have examined so far, there were actual calculation mistakes. No problems with the usage of quotes.

Top tips: Use notepad to construct the CSV. Put strings in double quotes. The front end is not the grader. It just is an assistant to help you. The actual grader works perfectly and we are able to see each students submission exactly as they submitted it.
You will get marks for any correct answers. And only the wrong answers will lose marks. If even one of your answers are wrong the UI will tell you have incorrect answers but will not tell you which one.

Hope that clears things up.
